Date: Tue 5 Jun 2012
Source: Yahoo!7, ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) report [edited]
http://au.news.yahoo.com/latest/a/-/article/13869292/more-positive-hendra-tests-in-virus-outbreak/


More positive Hendra tests in virus outbreak
--------------------------------------------
Another 2 horses on a central Queensland property affected by the state's latest Hendra virus outbreaks have returned positive test results. Biosecurity Queensland is dealing with outbreaks on a property near Rockhampton and another at Ingham in the state's north. One horse died on each of the properties late last month [May 2012].

The state government today [5 Jun 2012] announced that 2 more horses have tested positive at Rockhampton. The government says a dog on the Ingham property returned a weak positive result, and the animal will be retested. Agriculture minister John McVeigh has told parliament there is only one other recorded case of a dog being infected with the virus. "While laboratory research has been conducted on dogs, there has only been one other recorded case of a dog being infected with Hendra virus," he said. Chief veterinary officer Dr Rick Symonds says the virus was detected in the dog's faeces, which means it may have passed through the animal with or without causing infection.

"If the dog has become infected we'd expect the antibodies would be built up to that virus and we'll be ale to detect that in blood samples," he said. Mr McVeigh said since the start of 2011 there have been 13 Hendra virus incidents in Queensland, resulting in the deaths or euthanasia of 16 horses and 1 dog.

"I cannot stress enough that horse owners need to remain vigilant," he said. The animals have been isolated and the properties remain quarantined.

[byline: Melinda Howells]

